title A second rune category, ^-, proves the front-end shape generalizes past |- alone
prompt Keaton asked to "write this and finish the building round and document log and align and send" -- picking up the prior turn's own recommendation to build a small |- parser prototype as the honest next Glow-language step.
think Checked what already existed before writing a single line, rather than assuming the recommendation started from nothing -- searched for a rune parser and found glow/rune_bounded_trap.rye and its witness already real, landed 20260716.050000, earlier the same day, before this session's own HAWM/TUBE work began. Reading it in full rather than skimming: it already does exactly what my prior recommendation proposed -- real text ("|-  32", "|-  (lent records)") parsed to a BoundSpec, fed into the exact counter-checked-against-a-bound mechanism the RISC-V section of the design brief quotes. Building it again would have been pure duplication.
think Reframed the actual next step honestly: not "build the |- parser" (already real) but the thing worth doing *given* it already exists -- prove the front-end shape is a real, reusable pattern rather than a one-off special case built only because |- happened to need a bounded-recursion fix. Chose the cast rune (^-) as the second category, the smallest next entry in the design brief's own curated rune table with a genuinely different shape (a mold name, not a bound expression) worth proving the pattern handles.
think Mirrored glow/rune_bounded_trap.rye's own conventions deliberately -- same scope-discipline header comment ("no general expression parser exists here, and none is claimed"), same NUL-padded fixed-buffer + slice-reader shape for the extracted name, same "trim whitespace, scan to the rune's own boundary, refuse three named malformed shapes" structure -- rather than inventing a second style for what is structurally the same kind of small prototype.
think Designed the mold-name validation (refusing a leading digit) by reasoning from what the design brief's own worked examples actually are: an aura mold always starts with '@' (its own sigil), and a named mold is always a bare identifier -- neither shape could ever legitimately start with a digit, so refusing that case at the cast's own boundary catches a real authoring mistake rather than being an arbitrary restriction invented for the witness to exercise.
think Built and ran the new module standalone first (six claims, all GREEN) before wiring anything into the larger suite -- the same order of operations as every other addition this session: isolated proof, then integration, never the reverse.
think Wired the new rish wrapper into tools/parity_ch01.rish directly after the bounded-trap witness it extends, matching the file's own convention of placing a new lap at its own logical neighbor rather than always at the tail. Reran the full chapter afterward and confirmed the same pre-existing, unrelated copyForwards RED from the prior turn still halts the suite at the same earlier line -- meaning neither my new witness nor TUBE0 (both wired after that halt point) ever actually execute inside the full-chapter run, and the standalone proof from each is the only direct evidence either is real. Named this plainly rather than letting a full-suite "it ran" stand in for a claim it cannot actually make once an earlier assertion halts the chapter.
obs The discipline that mattered most this pass was checking for existing work before building -- a session moving fast across many turns is exactly where duplicate, wasted effort creeps in, and reading the tree honestly before writing avoided it here.
